\begin_layout Standard
The history of the neutrino can be traced back to electron energy spectrum
 observed in neutron 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-decay.
 While measurements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

- and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

-decay of atomic nuclei showed discrete spectral lines, the electron (
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 particle) exhibited a continuous energy spectrum.
 Experimentally, there were two observed particles in each decay process
 and classical physics dictated that the outgoing daughter particles should
 have discrete energies.
 The fact that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-decay spectrum was not this way posed a fundamental problem for physicists
 in the mid-1910s and later, was energy conserved? Two solutions were postulated
: either the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

energy conservation law is only valid statistically in such a process [...]
 or an additional undetectable new particle [...] carrying away the additional
 energy and spin [...] is emitted 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zuber2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The latter solution was supported by Wolfgang Pauli in a letter dated 4
 December 1930 to a group of physicists meeting in TÃ¼bingen, modern Germany,
 where he first proposed the neutrino
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In W Pauli's December 1930 letter, he referred to his proposed particle
 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

neutron
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which is not the same neutron known of today.
 At that point in time, the neutral particles inside the atomic nucleus,
 also called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

neutrons
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, had not been discovered, let alone understood.
 The neutron, which was discovered in 1932 by James Chadwick, has been formally
 associated as the neutral, cousin particle to the proton.
 It would be Enrico Fermi who would coin the particle in W Pauli's letter
 and solution to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-decay spectrum as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

neutrino
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 meaning in Italian 
\shape italic
little neutral one
\shape default
.
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Pauli's solution also predicted that the undetected neutrino would have
 half-integer spin, a quantum mechanical property of matter, since the observed
 particles in 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-decay did not conserve angular momentum.
 The existence of the neutrino and validation of Pauli's predictions would
 not experimentally verified for another 20 years.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The neutrino was first discovered in 1953 by Clyde Cowan and Frederick Reines
 using a nuclear reactor in South Carolina, U.S.A..
 Since then three types of neutrinos have been observed and from unique
 sources like the Sun and a supernova.
 Neutrino physics continues to be an active region of physics since neutrinos
 are unique probes to processes otherwise inaccessible in laboratories.
 For instance in the depths of the Sun's core where fusion occurs and neutrinos
 are created, neutrinos are able to travel through the ultra dense and hot
 medium of the core (over 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{7}$
\end_inset

 degrees Kelvin) and outer layers of the Sun and reach us on Earth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Neutrinos rarely interact with normal matter, meaning that they travel essential
ly unimpeded towards one's particle detector.
 The rarity of such interactions can be illustrated with the fact that given
 nearly 
\begin_inset Formula $7.0\times10^{10}\text{ neutrinos}/\text{cm}^{2}/\text{sec}$
\end_inset

 are incident on the Earth from the Sun
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To give some perspective to this number, this means 70 billion neutrinos
 are traveling every second through an area similar to one's own thumb nail.
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, statistically one solar neutrino can harmlessly interact with an individual
 in her lifetime.
 So this begs the question: how does one detect a neutrino? The short answer
 is one needs a ultra large volume of matter and a large enough flux of
 neutrinos in its path just to detect one given today's technology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scientists continue to be interested in neutrinos due to properties they
 exhibit.
 One of the more recent and surprising aspects about neutrinos is their
 ability to undergo 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flavor oscillations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 where a neutrino of definite flavor (type) is created and later observed
 as a different flavor.
 The impact of such oscillations could help explain the observed matter
 and anti-matter asymmetry in the Universe.
\end_layout

