\begin_layout Subsubsection
Chirality: How Neutrinos are Left Handed
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Chirality"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Neutrinos are observed to have anti-parallel momentum vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 to their spin vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 and the opposite is true for anti-neutrinos.
 This property is called helicity and is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:helicityoperator"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H}=\frac{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{P}}{\left|\boldsymbol{P}\right|}.\label{eq:helicityoperator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

While detecting neutrinos is hard as it is, the helicity is inferred from
 the daughter muon in charged pion decay.
 Since a pion has net zero (0) spin, the spin vectors of the daughters must
 also sum to zero.
 The muon from a 
\begin_inset Formula $\pion^{+}$
\end_inset

 decay has negative helicity (-1) hence the neutrino also has negative helicity.
 To confirm the anti-neutrino's helicity is positive (+1), the interaction
 requires both a charge (C) conjugation and parity (P) transformation as
 shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:DecayOfPion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 A C conjugation is a linear transformation that transforms all particles
 into their corresponding antiparticles while the P transformation inverts
 all spatial coordinates.
 Thus neutrinos are referred to 
\shape italic
left-handed
\shape default
 (LH) particles while anti-neutrinos are 
\shape italic
right-handed
\shape default
 (RH) particles.
 It turns out helicity is a useful quantum number to describe neutrinos
 and coincides with a property called chirality.
 To understand chirality and its relationship to helicity requires an analysis
 of the Dirac Lagrangian and Dirac equation.
\end_layout

