\begin_layout Standard
The Dirac Lagrangian for a free particle field 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 with half-integer spin can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}=\overline{\psi}\left(x\right)\left[\frac{i\hbar}{2}\sum_{\mu=0}^{3}\gamma^{\mu}\left(\overrightarrow{\partial_{\mu}}-\overleftarrow{\partial_{\mu}}\right)-mc\right]\psi\left(x\right)\label{eq:diraclagrangian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a four-component vector (spinor) describing a particle field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 are a set of four 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 matrices.
 The adjoint field 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\psi}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\psi}\left(x\right)\equiv\psi^{\dagger}\left(x\right)\gamma^{0}\label{eq:adjointfield}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\dagger$
\end_inset

 denotes the conjugate and transpose operations.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{\partial_{\mu}}$
\end_inset

 operator is a four-vector defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{0}=\frac{1}{c}\partderiv t,\partial_{1}=\partderiv x,\partial_{2}=\partderiv y,\partial_{3}=\partderiv z\label{eq:fourderivative}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

that acts only on the right of it while 
\begin_inset Formula $\overleftarrow{\partial_{\mu}}$
\end_inset

 only acts on its left (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\psi}\overleftarrow{\partial_{\mu}}=\partial_{\mu}\overline{\psi}$
\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 matrices are not unique and different representations dictate different
 kinematic regimes.
 The field equations are extracted from the Lagrangian using the Euler-Lagrange
 procedure.
 In general for a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 fields, the field equation are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\mu}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\left(\partial_{\mu}\psi_{r}\right)}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\psi_{r}}=0\quad\left(r=0,1,2,\ldots,M-1,M\right).\label{eq:eulerlagrangegeneral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 For the Dirac Lagrangian, the field equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\mu}\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\left(\partial_{\mu}\overline{\psi}\right)}-\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\overline{\psi}}=0\label{eq:diracELequation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which yields the Dirac equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[i\hbar\sum_{\mu=0}^{3}\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}-mc\right]\psi\left(x\right)=0.\label{eq:diraceqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The representation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 matrices that is useful to describe neutrinos is the 
\shape italic
Chiral representation
\shape default
 (also called the 
\shape italic
Weyl representation
\shape default
) where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma^{0}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & I_{2}\\
-I_{2} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\gamma^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & \sigma_{x}\\
-\sigma_{x} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\gamma^{2}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & \sigma_{y}\\
-\sigma_{y} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\gamma^{3}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & \sigma_{z}\\
-\sigma_{z} & 0
\end{bmatrix},\label{eq:gammamatrices}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 identity matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x,y,z}$
\end_inset

 are the Pauli Spin matrices given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{x}=\sigma_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}0 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{pmatrix},\quad\sigma_{y}=\sigma_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}0 & -i\\
i & 0
\end{pmatrix},\quad\sigma_{z}=\sigma_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Using the Chiral representation, the chirality matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{5}$
\end_inset

 (the fifth gamma matrix), is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma^{5}=i\gamma^{0}\gamma^{1}\gamma^{2}\gamma^{3}=\begin{bmatrix}I_{2} & 0\\
0 & -I_{2}
\end{bmatrix},\label{eq:gammafivedef}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is diagonal as well as Hermitian meaning that its eigenvalues are
 real and observable.
 Let eigenfunctions of the chirality matrix be denoted with subscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that the eigenvalue equations are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\gamma^{5}\psi_{P} & =+1\psi_{P},\\
\gamma^{5}\psi_{M} & =-1\psi_{M}.
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:chiraloperatoreigenvalueequation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The field equation solutions to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:diraceqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be decomposed into 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{M}$
\end_inset

 projections using two chiral projection operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{O}_{P,M}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi=\left(\hat{O}_{P}+\hat{O}_{M}\right)\psi=\psi_{P}+\psi_{M}.\label{eq:chiralprojections}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The chiral operators are explicitly given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\hat{O}_{M} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(I_{4}-\gamma^{5}\right)=\begin{pmatrix}0 & 0\\
0 & I_{2}
\end{pmatrix},\\
\hat{O}_{P} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(I_{4}+\gamma^{5}\right)=\begin{pmatrix}I_{2} & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{pmatrix},
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:chiraloperators}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{4}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 identity matrix.
 Taken together 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:chiralprojections"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:chiraloperators"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 indicate the free neutrino field is a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 minus axial vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{5}\psi$
\end_inset

, also referred to as V-A, under P transformations.
 This feature is what allows for the weak force to violate P-symmetry and
 CP-symmetry.
 Referring back to
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:diraclagrangian"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:eulerlagrangegeneral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the Dirac equation becomes a set of coupled equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}i\hbar\sum_{\mu=0}^{3}\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\psi_{P} & =mc\psi_{M},\\
i\hbar\sum_{\mu=0}^{3}\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\psi_{M} & =mc\psi_{P}
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:diraceqnchiral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where dynamics are set by the mass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the chiral projection operators are decompositions of the identity
 matrix, the simplest nontrivial solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi=\begin{pmatrix}\chi_{P}\\
\chi_{M}
\end{pmatrix}\label{eq:diracchiralspinorsgeneral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 represent two-component spinors.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:diracchiralspinorsgeneral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 the Dirac equation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:diraceqnchiral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can again be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}i\hbar\left[\frac{1}{c}\partderiv t+\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{\nabla}\right]\chi_{P} & =-mc\chi_{M},\\
i\hbar\left[\frac{1}{c}\partderiv t-\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{\nabla}\right]\chi_{M} & =-mc\chi_{P},
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:diraceqnchiralspinors}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{\nabla}=\sigma_{x}\partderiv x+\sigma_{y}\partderiv y+\sigma_{z}\partderiv z.\label{eq:matrixdotproduct}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the limiting case of vanishing mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m\rightarrow0\right)$
\end_inset

, as is in the SM, the free particle field equations in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:diraceqnchiralspinors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 decouple into
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\left(\frac{E}{c}+\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{P}\right)\chi_{P} & =0,\\
\left(\frac{E}{c}-\boldsymbol{\sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{P}\right)\chi_{M} & =0,
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:diraceqnchiralmassless}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the differential operators have been evaluated as the particle's energy
 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and momentum three-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

.
 For massless neutrinos, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{P}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{P}$
\end_inset

, describe particles of negative energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E=-\left|\boldsymbol{P}\right|c$
\end_inset

 which in the context of quantum field theory are interpreted as antiparticles
 traveling backwards in time.
 Conversely, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{M}$
\end_inset

 have positive energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\left|\boldsymbol{P}\right|c$
\end_inset

 and which means they are particles traveling forward in time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If one also multiplies 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:diraceqnchiral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{5}\gamma^{0}$
\end_inset

 and using the fact that the spin operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\Sigma}=i\left(\gamma^{2}\gamma^{3},\gamma^{3}\gamma^{1},\gamma^{1}\gamma^{2}\right)=\gamma^{0}\gamma^{k}\gamma^{5}\quad\left(k=1,2,3\right)\label{eq:spinoperatorgammamatrices}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

each decoupled equation becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\cdot\boldsymbol{P}}{\left|\boldsymbol{P}\right|}\psi_{P,M}=\gamma^{5}\psi_{P,M}=\pm\psi_{P,M},\label{eq:chiralhelicityrelationship}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where one recognizes that helicity and chiral states are the same for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 only.
 Thus the labels 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 actually are identical to the LH and RH helicity labels, respectively.
 Using the results on helicity from before, a neutrino is always observed
 as a LH particle while the anti-neutrino is always observed as a RH antiparticl
e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observation of only LH neutrinos and RH anti-neutrinos is an important
 feature in the SM.
 However, since neutrinos are known to have mass from oscillations, it is
 theoretically possible to observe a RH neutrino and LH anti-neutrino.
 That would require boosting to a highly relativistic reference frame with
 respect to the laboratory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Neutrino Oscillations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Neutrino-Oscillations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Neutrino oscillations are the observation of a neutrino produced of definite
 flavor and later observed as a different flavor.
 This phenomenon was first observed as a deficit of neutrinos for a number
 of atmospheric and solar neutrino experiments.
 The deficit also seemed more pronounced for atmospheric neutrinos as the
 distance from their source increased.
 For neutrino oscillations to occur, at least one neutrino must be massive.
 This observation firmly established that the SM is wrong with its prediction
 of massless neutrinos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first indication of neutrino oscillations was from the Ray Davis Homesteak
 Mine experiment which began in the 1960s.
 Ray Davis was an expert Chemist and designed a radiochemical experiment
 to measure the flux of neutrinos from Sun.
 The purpose of this experiment was to test John Bahcall's prediction of
 the fusion rate in the Sun and neutrino flux from it as well.
 Davis' experiment would need to operate for many years to collect enough
 statistics due to expected low capture rate.
 Measurements continued into the 1980s and showed that the flux of neutrinos
 as measured at Homesteak was about 1/3 the expected rate and became known
 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Solar Neutrino Problem.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The primary solutions were either the the solar model was incorrect or
 the neutrino capture cross section is incorrect somehow.
 The Sudbury Neutrino Observatory (SNO) was able to resolve this problem
 by making a model-independent measurement of the solar neutrino flux.
 SNO observed a 
\begin_inset Formula $\nue$
\end_inset

CC-to-NC ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.301\pm0.033$
\end_inset

, which confirmed that only about 30% of neutrinos arrive as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nue$
\end_inset

 flavors on Earth.
 Saying this another way, the majority of neutrinos arrive as the wrong
 flavor
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zuber2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another outstanding problem emerged with measurements of atmospheric neutrinos,
 in particular muon and electron types.
 Atmospheric neutrinos are produced when high energy cosmic rays strike
 atmospheric particles.
 These cosmic ray collisions generate mostly pions and kaons that decay
 into neutrinos.
 When trying to measure the 
\begin_inset Formula $\numu/\nue$
\end_inset

 ratio and comparing that with expected ratio, there was another significant
 deficit.
 This was particularly a problem as a function of the zenith angle for the
 Super-Kamiokande (SK) experiment.
 SK is a 50kt tank of pure water lined with thousands of photomultiplier
 tubes designed to observe solar and atmospheric neutrinos.
 It was the first experiment to perform a neutrino oscillation analysis
 that successfully explained the deficit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the phenomenon of neutrino oscillations has been understood for almost
 three decades, it was not predicted since oscillations require the neutrino
 has mass.
 The reasons why neutrino oscillations require massive neutrinos are explained
 in the next subsection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Two Flavor Derivation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Two-Flavor-Derivation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The phenomenon of neutrino oscillations can be described with elementary,
 non-relativistic Quantum Mechanics.
 Beginning with the SchrÃ¶dinger Equation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:schroeqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}-\frac{\hbar}{i}\frac{d}{dt}\diracket{\nu(\mathbf{r},t)} & =\hat{H}\diracket{\nu(\mathbf{r},t)},\end{aligned}
\label{eq:schroeqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}$
\end_inset

 is the Hamiltonian for the physical system, one considers a massive neutrino
 of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 in its rest frame (free particle).
 The Hamiltonian is diagonal in this case, which acting on 
\begin_inset Formula $\diracket{\nu_{j}}$
\end_inset

 results in the eigenvalue equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{H}\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t)}=E_{j}\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t)},\label{eq:schroeqntimeindep}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the energy of the neutrino 
\begin_inset Formula $\diracket{\nu_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:schroeqntimeindep"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:schroeqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $\diracket{\nu(\mathbf{r},t)}$
\end_inset

, one obtains the following
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t)}=e^{-iE_{j}t/\hbar}\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t=0)},\label{eq:schroeqnsolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t=0)}$
\end_inset

 is created with momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 at the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The time-independent solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:schroeqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is a plane-wave given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\diracket{\nu_{j}(\mathbf{r},t=0)}=e^{i\mathbf{p}\cdot\mathbf{r}/\hbar}\diracket{\nu_{j}}.\label{eq:schroeqnsolutiontimeindep}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before being able to describe neutrino oscillations, the basis states must
 be defined.
 For this example, consider that there are only two eigenstates, labeled
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

, in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mass
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 basis with definite mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 However, experiments can produce neutrinos, as well as probe them, only
 of definite 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flavor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, denoted by a Greek letter subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Let the generated neutrino, which is a linear superposition of mass states
 1 and 2, have momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 and flavor 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Since both mass eigenstates share the same momentum momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 (but not energy!), the exponential term in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:schroeqnsolutiontimeindep"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is an overall phase that will cancel out later.
 One can postulate a linear transformation, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, between the basis states given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:pmnstwodimgen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix}\nu_{\alpha}\\
\nu_{\beta}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}U_{11} & U_{12}\\
U_{21} & U_{22}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\nu_{1}\\
\nu_{2}
\end{bmatrix}\label{eq:pmnstwodimgen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This linear transformation must be a unitary matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U^{-1}=U^{\dagger},\dagger=\text{transpose conjugate}\right)$
\end_inset

 since the states 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 constitute a complete orthonormal basis in the mass basis.
 With this unitary property, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be written as a rotation matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix}\nu_{\alpha}\\
\nu_{\beta}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rc}
\cos(\theta) & \sin(\theta)\\
-\sin(\theta) & \cos(\theta)
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\nu_{1}\\
\nu_{2}
\end{bmatrix},\label{eq:pmnstwodimangle}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the angle between the two bases.
 One can imagine this transformation between bases as shown in 
