 This equation is not, however, terribly useful in the laboratory frame
 since it is hard to design an experiment where the travel time an individual
 neutrino is well known.
 Instead, one can make useful approximations that are accessible in the
 laboratory frame.
 Since neutrinos are nearly massless, they travel very close to the speed
 of light.
 Therefore time 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is replaced with 
\begin_inset Formula $L/c$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the distance between the neutrino origin and detection and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is now the speed of light in vacuum.
 One can also approximate the energy of the mass eigenstate as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
