\begin_layout Standard
If neutrinos are their own antiparticles, they do not follow the Dirac Equation
 but do follow the Majorana Equation.
 This adds two (in general 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

) more CP violating Majorana phases, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, to the MNSP matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{\text{MNSP}}\rightarrow U_{\text{MNSP}}\times\stackrel{U_{\text{Majorana}}}{\overbrace{\begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & e^{i\alpha} & 0\\
0 & 0 & e^{i\beta}
\end{bmatrix}}}.\label{eq:mnspdecomposedmajorana}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Unfortunately, neutrino oscillations are not able to probe the Majorana
 phases since the Majorana matrix is diagonal.
 The question of if neutrinos are Majorana (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\overline{\nu})$
\end_inset

 or Dirac (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\neq\overline{\nu})$
\end_inset

 particles is an open question and is being explored by non-oscillation
 experiments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full three flavor oscillation probability is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\mathcal{P}\left(\nu_{\alpha}\rightarrow\nu_{\beta}\right)=\delta_{\alpha\beta}-4 & \sum_{j=1}^{3}\left[\sum_{i>j}^{3}\text{Re}\left(K_{\alpha\beta,ij}\right)\sin^{2}\left(\phi_{ij}\right)\right]\\
+4 & \sum_{j=1}^{3}\left[\sum_{i>j}^{3}\text{Im}\left(K_{\alpha\beta,ij}\right)\sin\left(\phi_{ij}\right)\cos\left(\phi_{ij}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:threeflavorprobgeneral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{\alpha\beta,ij}=U_{\alpha i}U_{\beta_{i}}^{*}U_{\alpha j}^{*}U_{\beta j}\label{eq:threeflavorprobgeneralK}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

encapsulates the MNSP matrix elements and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{ij}=\frac{\Dm ijc^{3}}{4\hbar}\frac{L}{E_{\nu}}.\label{eq:threeflavorprobgeneralphi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since CP violation means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(\nuparticle{\alpha}\rightarrow\nuparticle{\beta\neq\alpha}\right)\neq\mathcal{P}\left(\antinuparticle{\alpha}\rightarrow\antinuparticle{\beta\neq\alpha}\right),$
\end_inset

 CP violating terms must be an odd function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\text{CP}}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the following examples, muon neutrino survival and muon neutrino
 to electron neutrino appearance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
